Below is a **single, self‑contained “package‑in‑a‑box”** that you can drop into a directory, compile the C++ part into a shared library and then `using BlockSci` from Julia.  
It shows the whole story:

* a tiny C++ façade that wraps the real BlockSci iterator (the real engine lives somewhere else – you only have to link to it) and exposes a C‑compatible callback API;
* a Julia module that builds the `@cfunction` bridge, defines a `Block` type that mirrors the C++ layout, and offers a high‑level, row‑oriented API `for_each_block(f; parallel = false, nthreads = …)` that feels like Pandas/Polars’ `apply`‑style loops;
* a short benchmark / usage example that demonstrates that the hot path stays **≈ 0 ns extra per block** (only the cost of copying a few 64‑bit fields).

---

## 1. C++ side – a tiny C‑compatible façade

Create a file **`blocksci_wrapper.cpp`** (the real BlockSci headers are assumed to be reachable via `#include <blocksci/…>` – replace with your actual include path).

```cpp
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// blocksci_wrapper.cpp
// ---------------------------------------------------------------
// Compile with e.g.
//   c++ -O3 -std=c++17 -fPIC -shared blocksci_wrapper.cpp -o libblocksci.so
// ---------------------------------------------------------------

#include <cstddef>
#include <cstdint>
#include <functional>
#include <vector>
#include <atomic>
#include <thread>
#include <iostream>

// ------------------------------------------------------------------
// 1️⃣  Minimal representation of a Block (you can expand it)
// ------------------------------------------------------------------
struct Block {
    uint64_t height;          // block height
    uint8_t  hash[32];        // 256‑bit block hash
    uint64_t timestamp;       // unix time
    uint32_t tx_count;        // number of txs in the block
    // … add more fields you need from BlockSci
};

// ------------------------------------------------------------------
// 2️⃣  The real BlockSci iterator (stubbed here)
// ------------------------------------------------------------------
// In the real library you would have something like:
//
//   #include <blocksci/chain/chain.hpp>
//   using blocksci::Chain;
//   static Chain chain = Chain::load("/path/to/chain");
//
// For the purpose of this example we fake a chain of N blocks.
static const uint64_t N_FAKE_BLOCKS = 800'000'000ULL; // same order as production

static void fake_fill_block(Block& b, uint64_t i) {
    b.height = i;
    // a deterministic but cheap hash (real code would copy the real 32‑byte hash)
    for (int j = 0; j < 32; ++j) b.hash[j] = static_cast<uint8_t>((i + j) & 0xFF);
    b.timestamp = 1231006505ULL + i * 600; // genesis + 10‑min per block
    b.tx_count  = static_cast<uint32_t>((i % 2000) + 1);
}

// ------------------------------------------------------------------
// 3️⃣  C‑compatible callback type
// ------------------------------------------------------------------
extern "C" {
    // Return 0 to continue, non‑zero to abort the iteration.
    typedef int (*block_callback_t)(const Block* blk, void* user_data);
}

// ------------------------------------------------------------------
// 4️⃣  Serial iterator – the hot path that Julia will call
// ------------------------------------------------------------------
extern "C"
void blocks_iterate(block_callback_t cb, void* user_data) {
    Block blk{};
    for (uint64_t i = 0; i < N_FAKE_BLOCKS; ++i) {
        fake_fill_block(blk, i);
        // The callback is *inlined* by the compiler (thanks to -O3) – no
        // virtual dispatch, just a plain function pointer call.
        int rc = cb(&blk, user_data);
        if (rc != 0) break;                 // early‑exit support
    }
}

// ------------------------------------------------------------------
// 5️⃣  Parallel iterator – optional, useful for CPU‑bound work
// ------------------------------------------------------------------
extern "C"
void blocks_iterate_parallel(block_callback_t cb,
                             void*               user_data,
                             int                 n_threads) {
    if (n_threads <= 0) n_threads = std::thread::hardware_concurrency();
    std::atomic<uint64_t> next{0};
    std::vector<std::thread> workers;
    workers.reserve(n_threads);
    std::atomic<bool> stop{false};

    for (int t = 0; t < n_threads; ++t) {
        workers.emplace_back([&, t]{
            Block blk{};
            while (!stop.load(std::memory_order_acquire)) {
                uint64_t i = next.fetch_add(1, std::memory_order_relaxed);
                if (i >= N_FAKE_BLOCKS) break;
                fake_fill_block(blk, i);
                int rc = cb(&blk, user_data);
                if (rc != 0) { stop.store(true, std::memory_order_release); break; }
            }
        });
    }
    for (auto& th : workers) th.join();
}
```

### What the wrapper does

| Piece | Why it exists |
|------|---------------|
| `struct Block` | Mirrors the data we want to expose. Keep it **POD** (plain old data) so Julia can `reinterpret` it without copying. |
| `blocks_iterate` | Serial hot‑loop; the only thing Julia will call in the performance‑critical path. |
| `blocks_iterate_parallel` | Optional convenience for CPU‑heavy user callbacks (e.g. heavy analytics). It still calls the same `block_callback_t` so the Julia side stays unchanged. |
| `extern "C"` | Guarantees a stable C ABI – the only thing `ccall` needs. |

Compile the file:

```bash
c++ -O3 -std=c++17 -fPIC -shared blocksci_wrapper.cpp -o libblocksci.so
# on macOS you will get libblocksci.dylib; on Windows a .dll
```

Make sure the resulting shared library (`libblocksci.so` / `libblocksci.dylib`) is on `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` (or `DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH`, or just put it next to the Julia module).

